"Harada T., Takenaka S., Maihara S., Ito K., Tamura T.","Changes in life-history traits of the water strider Aquarius paludum in accordance with global warming",2011,"Physiological Entomology","36","4",,"309","316",,,10.1111/j.1365-3032.2011.00798.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80655148934&partnerID=40&md5=246dcc4f1c3289b161fd4e7d17662363","Laboratory of Environmental Physiology, Graduate School of Integrated Sciences of Human and Nature, Kochi University, Kochi, Japan","Harada, T., Laboratory of Environmental Physiology, Graduate School of Integrated Sciences of Human and Nature, Kochi University, Kochi, Japan; Takenaka, S., Laboratory of Environmental Physiology, Graduate School of Integrated Sciences of Human and Nature, Kochi University, Kochi, Japan; Maihara, S., Laboratory of Environmental Physiology, Graduate School of Integrated Sciences of Human and Nature, Kochi University, Kochi, Japan; Ito, K., Laboratory of Environmental Physiology, Graduate School of Integrated Sciences of Human and Nature, Kochi University, Kochi, Japan; Tamura, T., Laboratory of Environmental Physiology, Graduate School of Integrated Sciences of Human and Nature, Kochi University, Kochi, Japan","Seasonal records of nymphs of the water strider Aquarius paludum Fabricius (Heteroptera: Gerridae) at a waterway in Kochi prefecture, Japan (33°00'N to 33°30'N), in 2007, show that populations of new generation adults occur four or more times during the year, in mid and late May; late July to early August; September; and October to November. In laboratory experiments, more than 50% of adults are reproductive, irrespective of photoperiod, and this ratio increases to 80% even under a short-day LD 11.5 13.5 h photocycle, which corresponds to the winter season at Kochi (33°N). There is a diminishing photoperiodic response in relation to the induction of diapause compared with measurements made in previous years (1995-1997), suggesting that reproduction may be possible over a much longer period in the near future (and even in winter) if local climate warming is sustained. A high proportion of males sampled in 2008 have small testes and a high proportion of females do not have mature oöcytes even in summer. This contrasts with earlier data showing that the testis volume index for the same period is greater in 1995-1997, and that 75% of females have mature oöcytes. These changes suggest that the Kochi-Nankoku population of A. paludum is beginning to show partial aestivation. Overwintering adults of both sexes are found to have no mature flight muscles in October/November 2008. This is in marked contrast with earlier data from 1995 and 2004. Adults that are reared in the laboratory also show a lower flight propensity in response to shorter day lengths. The absence of mature flight muscles in the autumn and lower flight propensity under shorter days may indicate a cessation of dispersal between the summer habitats and overwintering sites on land far from the waterways. Taken together, these data suggest that populations of A. paludum in the Kochi-Nankoku region are continuing to show adaptive changes, apparently in relation to global warming. © 2011 The Authors. Physiological Entomology © 2011 The Royal Entomological Society.","Adult diapause; Aestivation; Dispersal; Photoperiodism; Semi-aquatic bug; Voltinism","adult; aquatic organism; dispersal; estivation; fitness; flight; global warming; insect; life history trait; muscle; overwintering; photoperiod; temporal record; voltinism; Japan; Kochi [Shikoku]; Shikoku; Aquarius paludum; Gerridae; Heteroptera; Nepomorpha",,,,,,"Andersen, N.M., Phylogeny and taxonomy of waterstriders, genus Aquarius Schellenberg (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae), with a new species from Australia. (1990) Steenstrupia, 16, pp. 37-81; Bale, J.S., Hayward, S.A.L., Insect overwintering in a changing climate. (2010) Journal of Experimental Biology, 213, pp. 980-994; Bradshaw, W.E., Holzapfel, C.M., Genetic shift in photoperiodic response correlated with global warming (2001) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 98, pp. 14509-14511; Chen, Y., Ma, C., Effect of global warming on insect: a literature review. (2011) Acta Ecologica Sinica, 30, pp. 2159-2172; Danks, H.V., (1987) Insect Dormancy: An Ecological Perspective., , Biological Survey of Canada (Terrestrial Arthropods), Canada; Gomi, T., Seasonal adaptations of the fall webworm Hyphantria cunea (Drury) (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae) following its invasion of Japan. (2007) Ecological Research, 22, pp. 855-861; Gomi, T., Nagasaka, M., Fukuda, T., Hagihara, H., Shifting of the life cycle and life-history traits of the fall webworm in relation to climate change. (2007) Entomologia Experimentalis et Applicata, 125, pp. 179-184; Hance, T., van Baaren, J., Vernon, P., Boivin, G., Impact of extreme temperatures on parasitoids in a climate change perspective. (2007) Annual Review of Entomology, 52, pp. 107-126; Harada, T., A preliminary study on effects of nymphal density on nymphal duration and reproduction in the water strider, Aquarius paludum. (1994) Research Reports of Kochi University (Natural Science), 43, pp. 123-129; Harada, T., Life history traits of long- and short-winged adults in a water strider, Aquarius paludum amamiensis (Miyamoto). (1998) Entomological Science, 1, pp. 179-184; Harada, T., Comparative study of diapauses regulation and life history traits among four species of water striders, Aquarius paludum, Gerris latiabdominis, G. nepalensis and G. gracilicornis. (2003) Recent Research Developments in Entomology, 4, pp. 77-98; Harada, T., Nishimoto, T., Feeding conditions modify the photoperiodically induced dispersal of the water strider, Aquarius paludum (Heteroptera: Gerridae). (2007) European Journal of Entomology, 104, pp. 33-37; Harada, T., Numata, H., Two critical daylengths for the determination of wing forms and the induction of adult diapause in the water strider, Aquarius